Below is an excerpt from her travel diary.    I used to know Cuba as a leftist legend, that mythical island of Castro and Che. Cuba was the tropical paradise where rugged revolutionaries huddled in fields and strived to execute a guerilla genius. Cuba symbolized "by the people for the people," with its reclaimed socialist and autonomous state. And because developing-world David triumphed over imperialist Goliath, Cuba was one of the most captivating stories of all time.    At the end of that short time abroad, I felt like I knew Cuba not as an intimate, but rather as friendly acquaintance. I had mixed feelings, but knew that I'd miss the place. I wouldn't miss the heavy air that held smoke from quick burning cigarettes and dampened notebook paper. And I'd be glad to be over feeling confused by the contradictions. But, I would miss the decrepit old buildings, the rhythmic Spanish language, and the people who stop and talk with you on the street. And I'd miss Cuba's religion, because whether sustained by Catholicism or Santeria, that nation exists only by its own faith.    Sunday    Sunday morning feels hot and sticky. A thick, dirty heat that's reminiscent of New York summers clings to my body along with sour sheets. I rise out of bed and hang my top half out of the open window for a view of Havana at daytime. Below Saint John Hotel on Calle Twenty-three, men wearing shirtsleeves and women dressed in blouses walk to work. I'm not sure whether they're walking slowly because of the heat or because Cuba isn't going anywhere in a hurry. I see a narrow and grainy road traversed by long busses and boxy autos. Even Cuban cars look tired. Most need transmission replacement. New paint. A tall, once white apartment building stands about two blocks up in to the city.    In the afternoon, our group takes a tour of Old Havana. I see laundry lines hanging overhead between crumbling, colonial government buildings and mansions that Fidel redistributed post-revolution as apartments for the poor. Today, nothing in Havana can afford to exist merely for show. It feels surreal to know that people live above a shiny and fenced in fountain at Plaza Mayor, in the scaffold-supported structures that in The States would be officially condemned.    A middle-aged dusty brown woman sells libros de los Cubanos from the entryway to her apartment building. I see a tattered book holding Jose Marti's poetry collection. It stands on a four-tier rack along with several other heavily used books.    We pass by a modern looking building with black walls and deep orange trim. It's a luxury hotel and one of American writer Ernest Hemmingway's old haunts. Further away from Old Havana's center, in a small leafy courtyard, a live band plays American jazz music. "When The Saint's Go Marching In." Stilt walkers dressed in homemade clown costumes entertain a large crowd. A few group members break stride to circle three times around a wishing tree. An old woman stops me to ask for bath soap. I give her a box of toothpaste because it's all I've got in my knapsack. Shipments of soap, toothpaste, laundry detergent, and similar goods come to Cuba every two months by government ration. It's common practice and quite expected for locals to ask tourists for extra toiletries. The woman smiles, gives me a hug and a cheek kiss, and tells me her grandson lives in New York. I join back up with the group and board our blue exterior, red vinyl interior bus.    Tuesday    Our little blue bus rides through Havana's tourist neighborhoods of Central, Vedado, Miramar, Buena Vista, and Marianao. We pass by Havana's private beach coastline and some of the grandest hotels I've even seen or imagined. They're all sprawling modern-built resorts financed by European and other Caribbean hotel companies. Some of the Miramar and Buena Vista architecture reminds me of parts of Los Angeles, California. The colorful, single and split-level tile roofed and adobe built houses aren't exact duplicates of The Palisades, but still look straight out of Beverly Hills. Some homes are even reminiscent of other L.A. neighborhoods, like the Spanish-style gems found in the Crenshaw District and South Central. I think about how seemingly divergent places and people are more similar than the differences between them that we create.    In Marianao, we arrive at Havana's former country club, re-allotted and redesigned post-revolution as an art school. The school is symbol of elitism transformed into education. Back before '59, only Blancos had been allowed to putt around on the club green. A former mulatto president even got denied membership. Today, our group walks among young people of all colors caring knapsacks, easels, and saxophone cases. Individual, unseen musicians play everywhere, but their sounds come together in a sort of campus melody. Our guide points out a large empty room that holds about 50 chairs.    "That's where they used to hold all the big banquets and parties," he says. Today the room serves as a lecture hall. I finally spot a girl playing her violin.    Friday    Havana's National Museum proves Cuba and Fidel's immense appreciation for the arts. The building takes up an entire city block, albeit a small block, and looks grand as any museum I've ever seen in The States. On the bottom floor there's an open courtyard and a mandatory bag check. On each of the upper floors, displays of art from the colonial through modern periods sit on stands and hang from the wall. National's pop art section holds my favorite exhibit of the day, a wooden puppet show stage where painted carvings of major historical figures plug in and out. Today on display, I see Jose Marti, Abraham Lincoln, Jesus Christ, and Napoleon Bonaparte. It's interesting that Cubans, or at least this particular artist, consider Lincoln and Napoleon part of their national and personal history. I both enjoy and feel a little skeptical about the idea of a person or nation choosing his or her own historical truth; which parts from a cultural development and personal heritage to boast upon or deny. Under the stage, in a 20-plus person pile, I recognize wooden replicas of Che and Moses. This work makes me think about whom I'd choose as my own historical icons. At least a couple of women.    My roommate commented to me how within any 10-year span, hundreds of icons and celebrities take center stage in the U.S. Actors, singers, writers, newscasters, dancers, models, conmen, inventors, doctors, athletes, lawyers, musicians, murderers, victims, chefs, rich men, and talk show hosts - all of their faces decorate magazine covers and public space advertisements. But in Cuba, after more than a hundred years since the liberation against Spain, and nearly 50 since ousting Batista and the United States, three political icons exists in public consciousness and fully occupy citizens' obsession. Jose, Che, and Fidel. There is no one else. Home     New York City   Stratford, Ontario    Naples, FL    Beijing                            Hi guys! Ni hao! Ciao! Bon Jour!             My name is Amy Zhang. I am a student studying at New York University (NYU). This  is a travel blog of some of the favorite places I have traveled to.    I think it is important to have some sort of documentation of one's travel experiences! Thus, I decided to create this travel diary and share my photos with all of you.       I have picked 4 locations to share with you guys. The first one is New York City , aka the Big Apple. This is where I am currently studying as an undergraduate student. The second location is Stratford, Ontario . I went on a high school trip there a few years ago and really loved it there. As for Naples , I went there last winter break (2010) and spent New Year's on the beach with my family! Not a popular tourist destination but it's really lovely. The fourth and last destination is Beijing , where I spent my summer interning at Cummins  as a Marketing Intern. Since I am an Asian American, I enjoyed exploring and learning about my heritage and culture.       Next semester I will be studying in Italy through the NYU Study Abroad program at NYU Florence. I am so excited! I will be traveling with my friends from college and hopefully meet new students studying at other universities.       All these travel photos have been documented by me, Amy, with my little black Canon point-and-shoot. Take a look at my travel photos and I hope you enjoy seeing things from my perspective!            And if you enjoyed checking out this student travel blog you should visit my Pinterest . It's photo collages of my different interests. Also make sure to follow me on Twitter, @vamosamyz        Love, Amy.
